    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA116-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaivu nīṭṭippa āṟṟāḷāya talaivi tōḻikku vaṉpoṟai etiraḻintu colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what SHE, who was unable to bear it when [HE] delayed marriage, said to the confidante, being desolate in the face of [her] comforting.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA116">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            tīmai kaṇṭōr tiṟattum periyōr</l>
<l>            tāmaṟin tuṇarka veṉpa mātō</l>
<l>            vaḻuvap piṇṭa nāppa ṇēmuṟ</l>
<l>            ṟiruveti rīṉṟa vēṟṟalaik koḻumuḷai</l>
<l>            cūṉmutir maṭappiṭi nāṇmēya lāru </l>
<l>            malaikeḻu nāṭaṉ kēṇmai palaviṉ</l>
<l>            mācciṉai tuṟanta kōṇmutir perumpaḻam</l>
<l>            viṭaraḷai vīḻntuk kāṅkut toṭarpaṟac</l>
<l>            cēṇuñ ceṉṟuk kaṉṟē yaṟiyā</l>
<l>            tēka laṭukkat tiruṇmukai yirunta </l>
<l>            kuṟiñci nallūrp peṇṭi</l>
<l>            riṉṉu mōvā reṉṟiṟat talarē.</l>
    </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l rend="indent3">“Great ones, even on the occasion they have seen harm [done],</l>
<l rend="indent3">will know [and] perceive for themselves” – don't they say so?</l>
<l>The intimacy with the man from the mountainous land,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the highly pregnant youthful elephant cow grazes to [her] fill by day</l>
<l rend="indent">on the rich shoots on top of the spears brought forth by the big bamboo,</l>
<l rend="indent">agitated in [her] center by a misformed embryo(?),<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vaḻuva piṇṭam nāppaṇ ēmuṟṟa</term>: thus the suggestion brought forward by J.L.C., which has the merit that it makes sense of an enigmatic line. Indeed there seems to be one parallel for <term xml:lang="ta">piṇṭam</term> in the sense of malformed embryo, namely PN 28.1, where we find an enumeration of child deformations. Otherwise one could also think of the elephant suffering from indigestion caused by a bad rice-ball (for <term xml:lang="ta">piṇṭam</term> in the sense of a rice-ball fed to elephants there are several parallels).</note></l>
<l rend="indent2">as the big fruit ripening in bunches that is abandoned by the big branch</l>
<l rend="indent2">of the jackfruit tree, is shed, falling into a cleft<note place="foot">Here the formulaic compound of <term xml:lang="ta">viṭar-aḷai</term> cannot be read in any semantically significant way.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent4">it has been dropped,</l>
<l rend="indent4">going into the distance<note place="foot">What of <term xml:lang="ta">cēṇ-um</term> here? And do we rather have to suspect a change of subject, despite the absolutive construction? Actually it is HE who is supposed to go into a distance.</note>, so that attachment subsides.</l>
<l rend="indent4">Without knowing [that],</l>
<l>the women of the good village with Kuṟiñci shrubs,</l>
<l rend="indent2">on which there were dark buds, on the mountain side with big stones,</l>
<l>even now don't stop [their] gossip on my account.</l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="12b">
    <l>For what reason don't they even now stop gossip?</l>
</lg>
        </lg>
